from matplotlib import pyplot as plt
import pandas as pd
from sklearn.datasets import make_blobs

plt.figure(figsize=(8, 8))
plt.title("Synthetic normally distributed dataset")
X1, Y1 = make_blobs(n_samples=[1000,100,500],n_features=2,random_state=1)
plt.scatter(X1[:, 0], X1[:, 1], marker="o", c=Y1, s=25, edgecolor="k")
plt.show()
In [2]:
from imblearn.under_sampling import RandomUnderSampler
from imblearn.over_sampling import SMOTE


fig,ax = plt.subplots(1,3,figsize=(15,5))

# original: 1000, 500, 100
print(pd.Series(Y1).value_counts())
ax[0].scatter(X1[:, 0], X1[:, 1], marker="o", c=Y1, s=25, edgecolor="k")
ax[0].set_title('original')

# 100, 100, 100
sampler = RandomUnderSampler(sampling_strategy = {0:100,1:100,2:100}, random_state=42)
X1_RUS, Y1_RUS = sampler.fit_resample(X1, Y1)
print(pd.Series(Y1_RUS).value_counts())
ax[1].scatter(X1_RUS[:, 0], X1_RUS[:, 1], marker="o", c=Y1_RUS, s=25, edgecolor="k")
ax[1].set_title('RUS at 100 objects per class')

# 200, 200, 200
sampler = RandomUnderSampler(sampling_strategy = {0:200,1:100,2:200}, random_state=42)
X1_RUS, Y1_RUS = sampler.fit_resample(X1, Y1)
sampler = SMOTE(random_state=42)
X1_SMOTE, Y1_SMOTE = sampler.fit_resample(X1_RUS, Y1_RUS)
print(pd.Series(Y1_SMOTE).value_counts())
ax[2].scatter(X1_SMOTE[:, 0], X1_SMOTE[:, 1], marker="o", c=Y1_SMOTE, s=25, edgecolor="k")
ax[2].set_title('RUS at 200 objects per majority classes \n SMOTE at 200 object for minority class')
plt.show()
